column11: Outcome determined by the total cases of polio, both wild (WPV) and vaccine circulated (cVDPD), reported by the Global Polio Eradication Initiative. In 1988 — when wild poliovirus was in more than 125 countries, paralyzing 350,000 people every year — the World Health Assembly launched the Global Polio Eradication Initiative to help eliminate the disease through a mass immunization campaign. In 2007 the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation joined other major health organizations already committed to the GPEI, contributing nearly $3 billion toward eradicating polio by 2019. Today 12 cases of poliovirus exist in two countries, and the Gates Foundation is optimistic polio could be completely wiped out this year.

Slightly upgrading chances of 2 countries with 10+ cases. Congo is most likely due to 9 cases of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus (cVDPV). Congo is planning to start its next childhood immunization push (10 million units) starting at the end of October, which may paradoxically increase the odds of one more cVDPV case by the end of 2017.

Afghanistan has had 5 cases of wild-type polio; more communicable but there is a nationwide polio vaccine push slated for August. The Congo currently has 7 cases, all vaccine-derived. Syria and Afghanistan added cases this week as of 7/19: Summary of newly-reported viruses this week: Afghanistan – one new wild poliovirus type 1 (WPV1) isolated from an acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) case and one new WPV1-positive environmental sample; Syria – four new circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) isolated from AFP cases.

Compared to a lot of questions I answer here, this was actually a nice one to look into because of how good the progress has been in the last few years. So far this year 10 of more cases have only been reported in Syria. Lookinng at the trend lines, there were two countries in 2016, three countries in 2015 & 2014, and 6 countries in 2013. Point in this disease is steadily retreating and the fact that no new cases have been reported since mid June. Pakistan's numbers are way down from previous years and I don't see polio exploding (relatively speaking) there in the next few months. That said, one new case per month in either Afghanistan or the DR Congo seems reasonable.
As per Khalid reasoning. I do think Polio will be eradicated this decade but not until the fighting in Syria/Afghanistan ends.

Based on the Global Polio Eradication Initiative's (GPEI) data, Syria already exceeds the 10 case minimum with 27 cases of cVDPD (http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/this-week/). Afghanistan is on pace to match last year's total of 13 cases given YTD data, and as an endemic country is always a candidate to exceed 10 cases. Pakistan is reporting significantly less cases based on YTD data compared to last year at this point, but is an endemic country, so the potential exists for a large outbreak to push it over the 10 case bar. However, current focus on eradicating polio in the country decreases the likelihood of a large outbreak not previously reported.
